Dialogue: 1,0:16:07.42,0:16:13.47,Default,,0,0,0,,The conquest of the Gin Drinkers Line, \Nwhich was initially believed to take a week or more,
Dialogue: 1,0:16:13.47,0:16:15.59,Default,,0,0,0,,was completed in just three days.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:16.48,0:16:18.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Kowloon Peninsula firmly under their control,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:18.82,0:16:22.79,Default,,0,0,0,,the Japanese troops \Nentered the continental part of Hong Kong unopposed. {lit: entered kowloon part of hk}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:49.35,0:16:52.84,Default,,0,0,0,,At 9:05 a.m. on December 13th,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.84,0:16:56.57,Default,,0,0,0,,the Japanese military representatives{/staff} \Nwith some English women in tow,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:56.57,0:17:00.92,Default,,0,0,0,,landed on Hong Kong Island, \Ntasked with encouraging a capitulation. {HA: to plead with the British women to encourage surrender. - no clue where plead part came from, michiannai toshite is "as a guidance; showing the way; guide" but i still dont know what it means - why'd they ask a woman to guide them also to an island in plain sight? I'd assume it means "to ensure safe passage"}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:16.51,0:17:17.27,Default,,0,0,0,,However,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.62,0:17:19.47,Default,,0,0,0,,the British reply was
Dialogue: 0,0:17:19.89,0:17:20.74,Default,,0,0,0,,"Never". {pretty sure it was "no" irl}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:21.72,0:17:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,With a single word, the commander \Nruled out the surrender as a possibility. {lit: in other words, it was one word that meant they'll never surrender}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.88,0:17:38.16,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese renewed their attack \Nwith continuous raids.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:38.93,0:17:42.10,Default,,0,0,0,,The scale of the disaster \Ndwarfed anything seen before. {unsure what he means: that never before intensity to inflict (damage); to deal; to give/to increase; to gather (e.g. speed); to pick up thing}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.67,0:17:54.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, on December 17th,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.86,0:17:58.03,Default,,0,0,0,,the Japanese army once again \Nput forward a surrender offer.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:58.85,0:17:59.70,Default,,0,0,0,,However...
Dialogue: 0,0:17:59.70,0:18:03.09,Default,,0,0,0,,The Governor-general of Hong Kong \Nas well as the Commander-in-Chief
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.09,0:18:06.83,Default,,0,0,0,,rejected flatly any kind of negotiations \Nabout surrender.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:06.83,0:18:08.87,Default,,0,0,0,,It is absolutely out of the question.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:08.87,0:18:13.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Moreover, I take this opportunity \Nto declare that we will no longer listen
Dialogue: 0,0:18:13.50,0:18:17.91,Default,,0,0,0,,to any proposition from the Japanese army, \Npertaining to this matter. {lit: we're not prepared to receive the contact from ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:26.64,0:18:28.50,Default,,0,0,0,,A squall is likely to come soon.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:29.50,0:18:31.44,Default,,0,0,0,,The moonrise is late tonight. {no clue what's the message of this}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.67,0:18:40.57,Default,,0,0,0,,At 9 o'clock tonight, commence the crossing. {actually "landing" but I think he means "embark to later land" because you can't exactly time landing like that}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:42.22,0:18:44.01,Default,,0,0,0,,As a matter of fact, my division,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:44.01,0:18:48.87,Default,,0,0,0,,includes a Los Angeles Olympic Games medalist \Nin breaststroke swimming, Lieutenant Koike Reizo. {I can't find any records of irl this guy taking part in this operation, but his name is spelled out clearly} {also technically "winner/champion" but he only was silver medalist so idk} {I think this is the event they are talking about, although irl it took place on dec 13th and here they depict a rather later date: A group of swimmers from the 38th Division, led by two officers, gather on the 13th to receive special training to swim across the harbour. The plan was then dropped as the group suffered losses during a British bombardment as whilst they assembled at Kai Tak.}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:49.29,0:18:54.77,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll form a volunteer division with the Lieutenant as its core and have them swim across to distract the enemy. {lit: bring to disorder; chaos; confusion; mayhem the enemy base/position}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:54.77,0:18:56.17,Default,,0,0,0,,We've no need for that.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.81,0:19:13.81,Default,,0,0,0,,In that thick black smoke, the British can't see us \Nrowing right past them even 50 meters away. {lit: from the british position, kaijo is not supposed to be seen - not exactly sure what's kaijo but has to do with the sea/landing/swimming/sea surface/traffic}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:13.81,0:19:17.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Besides, this rain renders the sea surface \Nimpenetrable to the eye. {lit: in this weather, kaijo is a complete darkness}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:18.65,0:19:21.74,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll repeat \Nwhat we did to conquer the Gin Drinkers Line. {lit: it's the same as ... breakthrough strategy/operation}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:22.41,0:19:24.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright, make arrangements for a massive landing. {lit: let's land all at once}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.46,0:19:37.71,Default,,0,0,0,,At 9 p.m., the Japanese army \Nstarted the crossing towards Hong Kong Island, {"landing" act. same as before}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.71,0:19:40.51,Default,,0,0,0,,virtually unnoticed by the British.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.47,0:19:44.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Not even when the Japanese soldiers \Nclosed to 90 meters away.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:46.24,0:19:48.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Second artillery observation post speaking.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:48.42,0:19:50.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Nothing out of the ordinary going on.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:50.35,0:19:53.02,Default,,0,0,0,,- such was the report, made during the landing.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.49,0:20:07.33,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese army landing was a complete success.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:07.90,0:20:08.83,Default,,0,0,0,,However,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:08.83,0:20:13.27,Default,,0,0,0,,the British troops counterattacked fiercely, \Nas their escape route was cut off.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:13.27,0:20:15.56,Default,,0,0,0,,The power plant, considered a vital position,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.56,0:20:21.26,Default,,0,0,0,,was defended by a hastily assembled volunteer unit{/self-organized unit}, comprised of about 70 British and French businessmen,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.26,0:20:22.41,Default,,0,0,0,,living in Hong Kong.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:22.88,0:20:29.68,Default,,0,0,0,,All had previous combat experience, but still, the youngest \Nmember of this formation was a 55 years old veteran. {lit: was a 55 y.o. old soldier}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:30.78,0:20:35.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Nevertheless, even after fully relieving \Nthe Indian Rajput battalion of fighting, {lit: after the rajput, whom they fought alongside with, withdrew}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.73,0:20:40.41,Default,,0,0,0,,this old mens' company managed \Nto hold onto the power plant for a whole day.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.20,0:20:47.99,Default,,0,0,0,,It's nothing like how it was during World War I.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:47.99,0:20:52.54,Default,,0,0,0,,They gave me this medal \Nfor what I did in the Spanish Civil War. {I would assume he means the 1936-39 civil war as there weren't any wars in spain prior to that period; then again, said war only ended 2 years ago and he makes it sound as though it happened 20 ago so idk}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:52.54,0:20:53.39,Default,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:53.79,0:20:56.40,Default,,0,0,0,,The Indian Rajput Battalion is retreating in full!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:04.76,0:21:06.76,Default,,0,0,0,,And with their tails between their legs! {lit: miserable; pitiable; shameful; deplorable; pathetic}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:07.24,0:21:10.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Let them{/does'nt matter}! We will defend this place until death!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:32.41,0:21:36.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Keep it up! Chiang Kai-shek is already leading \Nhis large army to our succor!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:36.04,0:21:38.04,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese army's back will be smashed!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.43,0:21:39.23,Default,,0,0,0,,However,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:39.66,0:21:44.38,Default,,0,0,0,,the promised allied army of Chiang Kai-shek, \Nwhom they put their reliance upon, never came.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.11,0:21:51.70,Default,,0,0,0,,It marched in the distance, far beyond the front line,{lit is "on the other side of the border/boundary" but idk what it may mean} \Nwest to east, just to disappeared again into the hinterland.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:51.70,0:21:54.48,Default,,0,0,0,,The British troops were plunged into despair.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:55.02,0:21:59.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Governor-General, after a long struggle, the reservoir \Neast of Mount Nicholson fell to the Japanese.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:04.68,0:22:09.43,Default,,0,0,0,,In want of fresh water and supplies, \Nthe civilians are fleeing Hong Kong in rapid succession. {/one after another}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:19.73,0:22:22.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Prolonging the fight any further is impossible.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:28.34,0:22:33.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Resisting any further would only \Nopen the way for more civilian deaths.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:37.56,0:22:41.90,Default,,0,0,0,,December 25th, time is 5:20 p.m. {actually the east of nicholson fell already on 20th so idk why they show this as related events}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.90,0:22:43.32,Default,,0,0,0,,The Governor-General of Hong Kong
Dialogue: 0,0:22:43.32,0:22:48.01,Default,,0,0,0,,and the overall commander of the British forces \NMajor General Maltby settled for surrender.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.01,0:22:53.62,Default,,0,0,0,,At the Peninsula Hotel on the mainland part of Kowloon, \Nthey met with the Japanese army headquarters.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:53.62,0:22:56.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It was exactly on the day of Christmas.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:56.62,0:23:03.10,Default,,0,0,0,,And then, to flickering candlelights, \Nas though in the celebration of the holy night,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:03.10,0:23:05.15,Default,,0,0,0,,the British signed a capitulation.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:05.50,0:23:10.30,Default,,0,0,0,,The Governor-General of Hong Kong especially \Ntook this defeat intensely. {lit: ...'s feeling of defeat was acute}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:10.30,0:23:11.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Stop it!
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.24,0:23:13.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't picture me!
Dialogue: 0,0:23:15.21,0:23:19.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Soon after, the Fall of Hong Kong, \Nwhich was believed to take four weeks at least,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:19.71,0:23:22.34,Default,,0,0,0,,was achieved in almost half the time.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.77,0:23:24.90,Default,,0,0,0,,A great victory achieved that promptly
Dialogue: 0,0:23:24.90,0:23:29.99,Default,,0,0,0,,was a sum of small details that the commander, leading his unit forward, must steadily keep in mind.  {unsure what he means: commanding a division man always heart ought to do problem consists of}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.41,0:23:35.22,Default,,0,0,0,,This one time, the young offensive mindset \Nof a junior commanding officer {lit: judgement attack - I think he means "the decision to attack"}
